description:
George was appointed Chief Executive of Westpac Group’s Consumer Bank in June 2015 and is responsible for managing the end to end relationship with consumer customers. This includes all consumer banking products and services under the Westpac, St.George, BankSA, Bank of Melbourne and RAMS brands.  

Prior to this appointment, George was CEO, St.George Banking Group. He joined the Westpac Group in March 2009 as Chief Executive, Westpac New Zealand Limited. Formerly George was Group Executive General Manager at National Australia Bank and prior to that, a senior executive in Commonwealth Bank of Australia's Institutional Banking Division.  He has also been a partner with the Boston Consulting Group and an officer in the Royal Australian Air Force.

In addition to being one of Australia’s most experienced financial services executives, George is a highly sought after board and advisory committee executive.  His current positions include;
•  Chair, Prime Minister’s Industry Advisory Committee on Veterans’ Employment
•  Chair, St George Bank
•  Board member, Bank of Melbourne
•  Governor, St George Foundation
•  Co-founder, Head Start Homes
•  Advisory Committee, UNSW Business School 

George is a passionate supporter and actively involved with numerous charities, including;
•  Amnesty 2020, Council member 
•  St Vincent’s Curran Foundation 
•  The Hellenic Initiative, board member

description:
Susie is a respected leader in the Australian financial services risk management industry, with a deep wealth of experience spanning over 25 years across financial crime, fraud, retail credit risk, and operational risk. Susie holds both a Bachelor of Commerce (Sydney University) and Executive Masters of Business Administration (MBA AGSM). 

As the Group Head of Financial Crime and Fraud for the Westpac Group, Susie is accountable for ensuring effective global financial crime risk management and compliance, encompassing fraud, money laundering, terrorism financing, anti-bribery and corruption, economic and trade sanctions, and tax evasion. This international role covers all retail and institutional banking divisions globally, including the Americas, Asia and Australasia. The scope of the role includes extensive transformation of financial crime global systems and process, strategic vendor management, and engagement with global regulators. In 2016 Susie’s contribution was recognized by being awarded the Westpac Risk Leader of the Year 2016, in addition to the CEO Service Revolution Award 2016. 

Susie’s prior roles within the Westpac Group include Head of Secured Risk, Head of Unsecured Risk and Fraud, all of which held accountability for credit policy and portfolio management, credit operations management, credit process re-engineering, as well as credit risk systems, tools and data development and management.   

Susie is a current board director of the Financial Crimes Exchange (FCE), and a former board director of the Australian Retail Credit Association (ARCA), the Banking Financial Services Ombudsman (BFSO), and a former advisor of the Banking Advisory Board for the Financial Ombudsman Service (FOS).

description:
Simone Tilley has a strong breadth across the business landscape working in Commercial, Corporate and Institutional Banks.  She has  ~20 years frontline experience in addition to leading her own family's manufacturing business (40 FTE), whilst also starting up a packaging business from scratch, later selling to a multi-national.  

Simone currently is the GM for ANZ's Retail Broker Division, responsible for ~56% of ANZ's Australian Retail Divisions lending flows, Third Party Deposits business ~8% deposit FUM for Australia Division.  

As a result of her transformative work uptiering governance, monitoring and oversight frameworks for the Retail Broker business, it has enabled the ANZ Retail Broker division to lead  many initiatives first to market.  

As a result of intense regulatory scrutiny by ASIC and Sedgwick, the industry recognised the urgent need for self regulation. Simone was appointed co-lead for the Governance, Data and Reporting stream in the Combined Industry Forum (CIF) where selected lenders, aggregators, industry bodies, ABA, Choice Consumer group and broker businesses, corralled to solve for regulatory issues to enable the third party industry to self regulate.   

Prior to this role,  she led Regional Business Banking Victoria and Tasmania, covering both Agribusiness and Commercial customers.  She also double hatted as National Head of Commercial Regional Bank, setting and executing strategy on a national scale.  

Previously, she was Director, Institutional Bank, setting and executing strategy for Global Agribusiness across ANZ's Global footprint.  

Simone has a broad perspective and varied experience spanning small business to institutional bank together with her own experience running a business in her own right.  She is renown for delivering performance excellence, leading transformational change whilst delivering financial outperformance through a highly engaged team.

description:
Sayed Rahmatullah Hussainizada has a strong passion for human rights, social justice and diplomatic solution to pressing issues within our society. He is an MC and a public speaker on social issues, refugee rights and cultural intelligence. 

Fluent in Dari, Farsi and moderate understanding of Urdu, Hindi and with basic knowledge of Indonesian, Sayed plans to build his career as an international lawyer and freelance journalist. He has a pronounced interest in the importance of diplomacy to address national and international issues to expand Australia's global role. Such issues include the need for cultural intelligence (CQ) and appreciation of diversity in the corporate and political sectors, raising the voices of unrepresented and disadvantaged people, particularly youth and raising awareness and acknowledgment of refugee entrepreneurism.  

Sayed runs Afghan Fajar Association Incorporated (AFAIC) -  a not-for-profit organisation that aims to establish a vibrant and connected Australia by providing education, assistance, social and cultural services to people of multicultural and disadvantaged backgrounds to grow an inclusive and harmonious nation. He sits on the advisory and board of directors of several not-for-profit organisations. Sayed is starting his own social enterprise focusing on culture and employment of migrants/refugees and people from disaster affected areas. 

Sayed has a Double Degree in Law and Journalism from the University of Technology Sydney. Sayed's goal is to combine his professional experience in the not-for-profit sector and strategic development with his interest in the law and the media. 

Sayed is the Winner of the Elizabeth Hastings Memorial Award for Student Community Contribution at he 2016 UTS Human Rights Awards.

description:
Julian Rebechi is General Counsel and Executive Manager | GM  at Swisse Wellness. He leads a team which oversees all legal aspects of the company, whilst also advising Swisse’s Board. In 2018, Swisse’s legal team was named Australia's “Legal Team of the Year" by Lawyers Weekly.
 
Julian joined Swisse in 2013 and has played a key role in many significant Swisse transactions, including Swisse’s $70m debt refinancing with Goldman Sachs and its landmark international joint venture with Procter & Gamble and Teva Pharmaceutical Industries Ltd. In 2015, Julian was part of the deal team which negotiated the momentous $1.67 billion acquisition of Swisse by Hong Kong listed, leading premium infant formula company Biostime International, and in 2016 the USD 400m bonds issue. In 2017, Julian was named "General Counsel of the Year - Finalist" at the 17th Lawyers Weekly Australian Law Awards.

Prior to joining Swisse, Julian was a Senior Lawyer in the Mergers & Acquisitions Group of Herbert Smith Freehills, during which he was involved in a number of high profile Australian corporate transactions, including AMP and AXA SA’s $14.4 billion acquisition of AXA Asia Pacific and TPG Capital’s (a leading US based private investment firm with more than $48 billion of assets under management) acquisition of Ingham Group. 
 
Julian has a Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Laws (First Class Honours) from the University of Melbourne and attended high school at Xavier College in Melbourne, where he was the recipient of the “Richard Pratt General Excellence Academic Scholarship”. During his law degree, Julian obtained first ranked Dean's subject prizes in contracts law, competition law, corporations law, property law and constitutional law. 

Prior to entering law, Julian was an international tennis player on the professional tennis circuit, achieving a world tennis ranking on the ATP tour and is a previous Scholarship holder and current member at Royal South Yarra Tennis Club.

description:
Mitchell Mathas is a restructuring and insolvency lawyer based in Sydney.

Practising in insolvency law since 1990, Mitchell’s experience is extensive.  He advises a wide range of clients including Australia’s more progressive insolvency practitioners, creditors, directors and shareholders, across industries including building, transport, finance, telecommunications, e-commerce and hospitality.

Mitchell has presented extensively on insolvency and related matters.

Mitchell has been recognised by the International Law Office, Client Choice Awards, receiving the Australian Insolvency and Restructuring award in 2010 and 2011.

His areas of expertise are: advising creditors, debtors and directors concerning their rights and powers in relation to insolvent or financially distressed companies and individuals, the effect and consequences of various forms of insolvencies, strategies for resolving obligations owed by insolvent or financially distressed companies and individuals, voidable transactions and debt recovery.

Mitchell has lectured “Set Off” in the Sydney University Debt Finance unit as part of a Masters of Law course since 1998. He is extensively published as an author and contributor on insolvency, bankruptcy, contract law and financing.

Angela practices in all areas of employment law, including litigation, advisory and M&A.

Angela acts on both contentious and non-contentious employment matters. Her workplace and employee relations experience includes advising on employee entitlements, preparation of employment contracts, managing legal risks associated with termination of employment, advising defence on discrimination claims, independent contractor arrangements, occupational health and safety and preparing employer workplace policies. Additionally, she is currently acting in the defence of a prosecution following a workplace fatality. 

Angela also has extensive experience advising on the employment and industrial relations issues of various M&A projects. Her recent experience includes privatisations, schemes of arrangement, IPOs and a range of private treaty M&A transactions. jobDescription2:
As a Lawyer in the Taxation Dispute Resolution and Controversy team of KPMG Law, I have had a wide exposure to a variety of taxation matters including Personal and Corporate Taxation, Superannuation, Transfer Pricing, Multi-National Anti-Avoidance (MAAL), the Diverted Profits Tax (DPT), State Based Taxes (such as Land Tax, Payroll Tax and Royalties) and Research and Development. 

I have conducted extensive case and ruling research and analysis, both in domestic and international jurisdictions (ITAA's, TAA's, TRs, GSTRs, OECD BEPS and the Model Tax Convention). From this research, I created a number of reference documents for statutory time limits, out-of-time objections, powers of the Commissioner in respect of statutory notes, and presentation documents for R&D and MAAL disputes. 

I have been extensively involved along the dispute continuum, from Client Risk Reviews, through to large scale Audit activity, as well as litigation. This has involved the drafting of responses to the ATO, submissions in respect of voluntary disclosures and penalties and interest, independent evidence review and regular liaising with clients to assist and better guide them through the process. 

Administratively, I have also been largely responsible for the ensuring compliance with firm-wide engagement and risk processes and protocols, as well as organisation of Continuing Professional Development sessions for our national team and the hosting of our national team teleconferences.

Outside of my team. I have assisted in launching the Sydney Graduate Committee by performing the role of Treasurer. As part of this Committee, I have regularly appeared as a panellist at Graduate and Vacationer events, as well as appearing in the refreshed 2018 Graduate marketing material. I have also participated in a number of firm initiatives, including the KPMG dragon boat racing team at the City of Sydney 2018 Chinese New Year event.

description:
Hi! I'm Rachel, and I'm the girl that's going to help you connect your business requirements with the technical implementation. I currently study Information Technology at UNSW, because I believe having technical literacy is essential in the success of any business. I'd describe myself as incredibly high-achieving and always willing to give things a go, because you gotta be in it to win it! I love tackling new problems and learning from them as a result. 

Outside of all that academic and career stuff, I love getting involved in university life - particularly societies and case competitions. Having an active role in the community has always helped me feel accomplished that I'm giving back to society. Beyond that, in my free time, I like to make YouTube videos on beauty, fashion and lifestyle to relax and share my non-work passions!

www.heylinni.com

www.kiyobox.com
jobDescription:
KiYO Box is an Asian Beauty Box, based on the subscription box model - but we like to
      refer to it more as a surprise box. It aims to highlight the benefits of Asian skincare to
      sensitive skin and introduce new and exciting products into our customers lives. The
      box has a different theme every month and holds 4-5 beauty products, alongside
      samples and surprise treats - All for $30 plus free shipping. We value a special
      customer experience, so we include personal, handwritten notes and quotes to build a
      friendship with our customers!

description:
I am currently working in civil litigation with diverse experience helping clients who have suffered damage in motor vehicle accidents, public liability claims, intentional tort/assault claims, medical negligence, professional negligence and nervous shock claims.

I have experience working in different jurisdictions in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland. 

I have worked on a catastrophic medical negligence claim in the Supreme Court of Victoria and a successful appeal in the High Court of Australia on the issue of advocates immunity. 

I am committed to achieving the best result for my clients.
